bios.Pa22e9a1: Abernathy was an employee of renowned iron shipbuilder and manufacturer John Laird.   Brunel corresponded with Abernathy regarding gridirons, and their price, for the Great Eastern.
bios.P0e9341b: William Edward Acraman was a Bristol iron-monger, engine manufacturer, boiler-maker and ship builder. He was a member of the town council and Merchant Venturers, a director of the Great Western Steamship Company, and supplied the axle for the paddle wheels in the Great Western steam ship.  In 1842 he won bids to build 2 vessels for the Royal Mail Steam Packet Company on almost identical designs to the Great Western, the hulls for which were built by William Patterson whilst Patterson was also superintending the hull construction of the Great Britain.
bios.P0e83f73: William Bruce Adair was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company and Great Western Railway.
bios.P4e1c83f: Airey was Astronomer Royal and corresponded with Brunel throughout the planning and construction of the Great Eastern.  Brunel initially requesting Airey's advice for establishing an observatory on board the ship
bios.P458a6f0: Allen was an engineer who sought information, unsuccesfully, about the engines under construction by Watt & Co. for the Great Eastern.
bios.P7b3ef34: Andrews worked for the North of Europe Steam Navigation Co, and wrote to Brunel about distilling freashwater from seawater in 1855.  This was apparently in response to enquiries made by Brunel over similar information provided by William Riddle.
bios.P178158f: Brunel sought advice from Appold during the earliest production phase of the Great Eastern regarding water pumps for the ship.
bios.B98521e5: Armstrong & Coles were asked to tender for ship's scuttles for the Great Eastern in Spring 1857.
bios.P285ff3b: Baron William George Armstrong was an industrialist who specialised in hydraulic power. In 1856 Brunel requested  assistance in planning hydraulic apparatus, apparently for the rudder of the Great Eastern.
bios.Be63242f: Atchison & Hathaway offered a gas illumination system for the Great Eastern in early 1856.  Brunel offered to visit and examine any working example, which was not provided.
bios.Pff6138c: Bach contacted Brunel in early 1856, apparently with a version of a light bulb which he thought could be incorporated into the Great Eastern.
bios.P17742af: Samuel Baker was a Director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company and core initial investor.  He acted as mediator between Brunel and John Yates, the ESN Secretary, when Brunel and Yates' relationship began to break down in late 1856.  In mid-1857, he expressed safety concerns about the Great Eastern's launch to Brunel.
bios.P7507bac: Barber was an assistant of Brunel who occasionally corresponded with suppliers for the Great Eastern.
bios.P3b4b37f: Barber was an early director of the  Eastern Steam Navigation Company.
bios.P12f6c80: John Barnes was a mechanical engineer who built steeple engines.    Brunel sought his endorsement for this engine design in propeller-driven ships - a design rejected by both marine engineers and the Royal Navy .  There is no evidence of forthcoming support.
bios.B4ec9e78: Barnett & Moss offered glazing supplies to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company, having been a provider for the Great Western Railway.
bios.P8261567: Sir John Barrow was Secretary to the Admiralty, 1840-45, whose patronage was sought during construction of the Great Britain.
bios.P23ec259: J P Bartum was a shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.  He is possibly John Bartrum, of Bath, local health secretary, who had property dealings with Thomas Guppy.
bios.P1f14a3d: Bates was an early hareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P2dc075f: Thomas Kington Bayly was trustee of the Great Western Steam Ship Company at its first inception.  He held a senior position in the bank of Miles, Harford & Co., Bristol bank to both the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.Pe30466e: Thomas Baynton was an early shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P2c5da36: Thomas Bazley was a director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company; he expressed concerns during the vessel's planning stage regarding the ships engine power.
bios.P4aae19d: Samuel Beale, of Beale & Co was a key figure in the Great Eastern project.  He was an investor with close links to Charles Geach, the principal backer of the ship, for whom 'Beale & Co.' were solicitors.  The Beale family were also involved in iron founding, and late in the Great Eastern project Beale was recommended to Brunel by Yates as a potential supplier of bespoke iron plate castings.  Although given a contract, Beale consistently struggled to provide supplies on time, and was never able to produce the bespoke sepcification of plate for which his firm was originally hired.  In 1859, he was named one of the directors of the Great Ship Company, the succesor company formed to complete the Great Eastern.   [By the late 1800s, Beale & Co. was being run by 'Arthur Geach Beale', further suggesting close links between the families.]
bios.P81dc82a: Beardmore appears to have been an employee of the Lancefield Forge, and provided Brunel with information on the submersion of paddle boards in 1855.
bios.Pfd54303: C A Beaumont was a river pilot in the Bengal Service.  He wrote to Brunel to inform him that the ship [Great Eastern] he was reading about in the newspapers of 1852 would be too large for the  Bhagirathi/Hugli [Hooghly] River, an initially muted place of navigation.  Brunel responded to Beaumont that he was already aware of these conditions.
bios.Pd6d0d54: Beckwith was an employee of Watt & Co, responsible for lowering and seating the boilers of the screw engine into the Great Eastern. Beckwith apparently did not follow his instructions, or claimed not to have received them when the engine placings were held up in the ships fitting out.
bios.P4070503: Chief of Piloting Department, Kolkata [Calcutta].  Bedford reported to Brunel in the early planning of the Great Eastern that the ships' draft was too great to navigate the Bhagirathi/Hugli [Hooghly] River.
bios.Pd75e0ba: Beecher assisted Brunel with the planning of navigational instruments early in the Great Eastern's planning.  These included a 'horizon instrument' provided by Beecher that Brunel discussed with G. B. Airey.
bios.Pbd854f5: Begbie appears to have been an associate of both John Scott Russell and the Great Eastern's first appointed captian, Cpt Harrison. He wrote to Brunel early in 1857 offering ship designs and assistance with gaining Admiralty contracts.  Neither appear to have come to any fruition.
bios.P903e7f6: Bell, of Hansons Olefiant Gas Co, offered gas lighting for the Great Eastern, which was not taken up.
bios.Pd29822f: Francis Henry Fitzhardinge Berkeley was a Director of the ESN.  He was an influential politician with close links to the Admiralty and British state.  During the building of the Great Eastern he offered a coating for the bottom of the ship, potentially based on naval practice, which was not accepted.
bios.Pf5718ef: Rev Edward Lyon Berthon worked on his own patented collapsing boat - a life boat - and from 1855 corresponded frequently with Brunel about its design and use.  Brunel did not commit to using it straight away on the Great Eastern, but did encourage Berthon to approach the admiralty for funding, suggesting that any work done for the national ineterst (presumably the Royal Navy) should not be done at private expense.
bios.P4ac4220: Edward Ludd Betts was a director and shareholder of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company who frequently corresponded with Brunel.  This correspondence typically regarded costs, discrepencies in ordering and work (raised by Brunel), and management of the Great Eastern's construction.
bios.P4dc3689: Bidfield sent Brunel information in early 1855 regarding the use of papier-mache as a fire retardent.  His firm, the Fibrous Slab Co., was eventually hired to supply the Great Eastern with fire-resistant insulation board.
bios.Bf65df6f: Binks & Stephenson provided wire rope samples for the Great Eastern in spring 1857, to the specification required by Brunel.  They informed Brunel that rope to his spec would total 84 tons.  It is not clear whether Binks & Stephenson ultimately supplied the ship.
bios.P1e777f9: Birch offered to fit out the Great Eastern with a library in mid-1857, and to serve as the ship's librarian.  Birch also offered to print special edition promotional literature.  He initially approached Joshua Field, rather than Brunel with this proposal, explaining that he had travelled on the maiden voyage of the Great Western, and sought to acquire a ticket for the maiden voyage of the Great Eastern.
bios.Pfed8966: Timber supplier from Clifton, Bristol, who provided Brunel, during the planning stages of the Great Eastern, with information about the types of Poplar used on the Great Britain
bios.P4bc3430: Henry Wollaston Blake was the London-based representative of engineering firm James Watt & Co, Birmingham, (formerly Boulton & Watt) and was responsible for the construction of the screw-propeller engines for the Great Eastern.  Blake was repeatedly reprimanded by Brunel for slow progress, and was the first major contributor to the project with whom Brunel's relationship became fractious.  When completed, the efficacy of the engines provided, and specifically the boilers, was sharply criticised.
bios.P46e6a63: Thomas Bold was an employee of Henry Wood & Co.
bios.Pb803b59: Charles Boulton referred Brunel to J Gibson as a supplier of papier mache for the Great Eastern.
bios.Pd8ac0fa: George Bower was one of many individuals who offered Brunel a system of extracting gas from coal for lighting the Great Eastern.
bios.B9c53c64: Brunel requested prices for iron supplies from the Bowling Iron Co late in the construction of the Great Eastern (winter 1856-7). Bowling were not able to supply the required material.
bios.P86b00b2: Boyle was an employee of Fox & Henderson who corresponded with Brunel regarding chain cables for the Great Eastern, which were to be produced in Birmingham.
bios.P118e345: Brunel sought advice from James Braidwood during the earliest production phase of the Great Eastern regarding water pumps for the ship.  Braidwood also contacted Brunel in 1855 with suggestions for a 'floating fire engine' to be used on the Great Eastern, being either a hose or steam engine in old-fashioned language.  Brunel replied, but the ideas do not appear to have been adopted.
bios.P2d61932: Braine was deputy chair of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company at its inception in 1852, and part of the original management board.
bios.P932c3e1: R P Brereton was a long-standing colleague of Brunel on the Great Western Railway.  He worked as a chief member of Brunel's staff, and was given very occassional deputy duties on the Great Eastern project.  He represented Brunel shortly after his death on the Great Eastern's first sea trials.
bios.P2dd235a: Robert Bright was a shareholder in the Great Western, later owner of the Great Britain, and member of a Bristol merchant family linked to Caribbean and Antipodean trade.  He was a business partner of George Gibbs from 1823, specialising in dry goods trading with the Caribbean, where he was also a plantation owner.  Bright was a major investor in, and director of, the Great Western Railway as well as a principal director and shareholder of the Great Western Steamhip Company. In 1850, the firm of Gibbs, Bright Company acquired the Great Britain from the Great Western Steam Ship Company and operated it to Australia for the next 26 years.  Bright died in 1869.  In the 1830s he received extensive government compensation paid to former slave owners after the abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/41207
bios.P06be75d: Briscoe appears to have been a legal or financial representative for the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  John Yates requested that Brunel send one of his own assistants with Briscoe during the escalating discussions with Scott Russell during early 1856.  He was also an early examiner of Watt & Co.'s completed engines for the Great Eastern.  Briscoe examined the screw engines supplied by Watt and remarked to Brunel that the boilers were defficient, being either 'badly made or seriously flawed', and suggested that someone more knowledgeable also conduct examinations.
bios.B6a4a23f: British Plate Glass Co were asked to tender for the cabin lights of the Great Eastern in the Spring of 1857.
bios.Pd604b6f: Rowland Brotherhood became, in the early 1840s, Brunel's principal ground and earthworks contractor for the GWR. His increasing involvement with the railway led to the building of a major ironworks at Chippenham and the beginning of a major engineering dynasty.  Brotherhood and his railway gangers were sent for by Brunel to cut the Great Britain out of the Bristol lock gates at Cumberland Basin when it was floated out in 1843; he was a significant investor in the Great Eastern, provided the iron launching rails for that ship and, after Brunel's death, forged replacement paddle wheels for the ship after a storm in 1862.
bios.P8c969bb: James Brothers offered Brunel 'non-combustible' straw board patterns for the Great Eastern, for which Brunel showed interest and requested quotes.
bios.Bed3e420: Brown & Harfield were engaged to build capstans for the Great Eastern site.
bios.B9a94bde: Brown Lenox & Co won the contract, in 1857, to supply the thickest chain cables used for the Great Eastern and its launch, being 6-inch chain link.  The firm had a number of problems with proving machines able to test the chain to its necessary strain, but as with most other experienced manufacturers who consistently struggled with the dimensions required in fabricating parts for the Great Eastern, they kept their contract through repeated attempts to satisfy the initial order.
bios.Pab2bbb2: Edward Brown Whitstone was one of many suppliers who contacted Brunel and the Great Ship Company in 1859 to enquire about coaling services for the Great Eastern.
bios.P2ec8d1d: Brown was a supplier of timber for the internal fittings of the Great Eastern in 1859.
bios.P50d1bff: Brown offered Brunel a 'new method' of marine propulsion in late 1856, coinciding with the problems arising with the Great Eastern's screw engines.
bios.P4a3cadb: C D Bruce was a member of Piloting Department, Kolkata [Calcutta], involved in discussions regarding the Great Eastern naigating the Bhagirathi/Hugli [Hooghly] River.
bios.P3e0fb75: H A Bruce was one of many suppliers who contacted Brunel and the Great Ship Company in 1859 to enquire about coaling services for the Great Eastern.
bios.P15ecbad: Isambard Kingdom Brunel was a key figure in the construction of the Great Western steam ship, central figure in the construction of the Great Britain steam ship, and dominant figure in the conception and construction of the Great Eastern steam ship.   A protege of his father, Marc Isambard Brunel, who helped conceive early mass-production techniques, as well as major structural and civil engineering works, Isambard Kingdom Brunel's career took an independet path when he became involved in Bristol's merchant and commercial community in the early 1830s.   After beginning work to build a bridge across the Avon Gorge in Bristol, in 1832 Brunel was hired to survey the city's floating harbour, an appointment that brought him into wider contact with the city's corporate patronage, specifically the members of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce, who led early debates about dock improvements, railway planning and steam shipping connections.  His appointment as initial surveyor and later engineer of the Great Western Railway was a result of contact with this group, as was his involvement with the city's Atlantic steam shipping endeavours. In 1836-7, Brunel proved critical to the creation of the SS Great Western, the first ship of the Great Western Steamship Company, by guiding the company toward Joshua Field of Maudslay, Sons & Field, as builder of the ships' engines.  Field was in turn connected to the leading edge of marine engineering, through figures such as Oliver Lang (structural design) and Samuel Hall (engine efficiencies).  Brunel superindented the production the Great Western's engines, but there is no direct documentray evidence that he led the ship's design.  His role was managerial and social.  In the Great Britain, Brunel's role was more central, being involved in core elements of design, and the critical decision to build the ship in iron and to adopt a propeller.  Brunel's report convincing the company's directors to do so recently gained UNESCO status for its historical significance.  Brunel's correspondence when building the Great Britain shows a great appetite for the expertise of other contemporaries, but also the first signs of rejection of sound advice in favour of his own approach.  This theme became characteristic in the building of the Great Eastern, in which Brunel attempted total control of design and planning, and accepted tenders and approaches from companies and individuals who submitted designs in accordance with these plans, and who often had the patronage of the Great Eastern's major investors, but who were not always leaders in the world of marine engineering.  The building of the Great Eastern also saw Brunel abandon searches for, and changes in, the conceptual layout of the vessel in the search of greatest performance, being wedded firmly to its original concept and design throughout.
bios.P65a1a3c: George W Bull was an American engineer based in Buffalo, New York who had supervised several sideways launches of large steamers onto Lake Erie.  He advised Brunel (unsolicited) to adopt a free launch of the Great Eastern into the Thames, with Brunel subsequently entering periodically into discussion with Bull about the technical details of sideways launches.
bios.B4d1d072: Burbage & Healy offered some form of exhaust system for the Great Eastern late in 1856, which was not followed up.
bios.P3d3890a: Joseph Burch offered Brunel designs for a new screw propeller in mid-1856.  Brunel replied that he had already worked on such designs himself, in 1853, which then raised a patent issue for Burch, whose work pre-dated 1853, and which he had shown to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  Brunel offered to acknowledge Burch's work, which Burch was not happy with, threatening breach of patent.  Any pursuit of the breach was not recorded by the company.
bios.P7257ab1: George F Burke, of the Imperial Gas Light Co, recommended Smith & Phillips to Brunel as a source of gas lighting for the Great Eastern.
bios.P05b81e5: James St George Burke was a Director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company, who expressed concerns about cost during the pre-construction phase.  He was a director, along with Samuel Beale, of Brunel's South Devon Railway, and an early promoter of the Great Western Railway and the Great Eastern Railway.
bios.P0f4d294: Michael Burke offered a system of compass correction to Brunel in 1857, which was unused.
bios.P61cc236: Henry Bush was a member of a prominent Bristol merchant family, president of Bristol Chamber of Commerce and director of both the Great Western Steam Ship Company and Great Western Railway.  He received a jointly dispersed compensation payment from the British goverment after the abolition of slavery, believed to be linked to John Cobhams estate:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/45209
bios.B295deea: C Dowson & Sons provided cabin fittings for the Great Eastern (and also hydraulic presses for the ship's launch).
bios.P282e424: C J Mare were asked in November 1856 to tender for casting of the SS Great Eastern's rudder.
bios.Pc784287: Caldwell was chief engineer on the Cunard steamer Persia.  Completed in 1856, it was an iron paddle steamer which when launched was the fastest vessel on the Atlantic, completing the crossing in 9 days, although with enormous consumption of fuel.  Brunel wrote to Caldwell to give him 'calculations' and 'opinions' on the Persia and its performance in mid-1856, and mentioned the importance of knowing exact results from the Persia's trials for the future of the Great Eastern, all of which was provided.
bios.P5cd1517: Robert James Roy Campbell was one of the intial members of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company's management board.  He was co-signatory with George Braine of the first ESN committee meeting in 1852.  Later, he was one of the principal directors of the Great Ship Company, the firm founded to complete the Great Eastern when the ESN went bust after the floating out of the vessel.  He quickly became arbiter between Brunel and Scott Russell, a position which he found uncomfortable.
bios.Pdda6deb: Captain Walcott (RN) was a shareholder of the Great Western Steam Ship Co and advocate of Bath interests in the company.
bios.P098283a: Carpmael contacted Brunel in 1855 to inform him that the 'governor' he was planning to use on the Great Eastern's engines represented a patent infringement.  Brunel replied that the governor had infact been patented by Sir Marc Brunel
bios.Pecb8088: George Carter offered Brunel propeller designs during the late stages of the Great Eastern's construction, which were not followed up.
bios.Paff32ce: W H Castle was an early shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.B87829af: Catto & Miller offered iron yards for the Great Eastern, however it is not clear whether they gained a contract.
bios.B738d100: Chance Bros Co were asked to tender for the cabin lights of the Great Eastern in the Spring of 1857.
bios.Pb446e92: Captain Edward Chappel (RN) was controller of Channel Packets, Royal Navy. He corresponded with both Brunel and pioneering iron ship-builder John Laird during propeller trials of the Archimedes.  Later Secretary of the Royal Mail, who purchased the Great Western on his advice.
bios.P9870413: Recommended by Engledrew, RN, to Brunel to lead the fitting out of the Great Eastern.
bios.P058f752: Clare offered to build metalic masts for the Great Eastern in 1855.
bios.P654d9f8: Clark corresponded with Brunel in 1856 and 1857 about oil gas lighting for the Great Eastern, but was not given a contract.
bios.Pe86743a: In late 1857, Clark offered an electronic bell system for the Great Eastern, (and also recommended suppliers of hydraulic presses for the ship's launch).
bios.Pf34a6ad: J B Clarke was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P7620205: Seymour Clarke enquired with the Eastern Steam Navigation Company about its coaling supplies in late 1857.  There is no record of further correspondence.
bios.P13489e4: Christopher Claxton was a member of a Bristol merchant family historically linked to Caribbean trade.  Claxton's father was a shipping merchant and plantation owner, and his elder brother William Claxton was treasurer of the Merchant Venturers as well as inheritor of the family businesses.  As a second son, Christopher took up a career in the services, and was a sailor in the Royal Navy during the Napoleonic Wars.  In the 1820s he was a ship captain for Bristol merchant vessels, and was appointed harbour master in 1834.  He was Managing Direcor of the Great Western Steamhip Company [GWSSco.] from its inception, and provided the company with useful contacts in the Royal Navy.  He retained links with Brunel long after the collapse of the GWSSco., and was frequently asked about basic nautical matters by Brunel during the construction of the Great Eastern, such as  rigging arrangements and the roles of sailing personnel.  His testimony formed a large part of the Brunel biography written by Isambard jr.
bios.Pa1fb1aa: William Claxton was elder brother of Christopher Claxton and Inheritor of the Claxton family business in Bristol.  He was a member of Merchant Venturers (historical appointers of harbour master, a role given to Christopher in 1834), and treasurer of the Merchant Venturers from 1841-73.  He was trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company at its inception.  William Claxton received compensation payment from the British government after the abolition of slavery:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/1722518733
bios.P65d0f5c: William Clay was a representative of the Horsefell Mersey Iron Co.  Clay and Horsefell Mersey offered Brunel quotes for the Great Eastern's rudder casting in December 1856.
bios.Pa39ae70: Clifton worked for Barnett & Moss, glazing firm who supplied the Great Western Railway and were initially positioned to provide glazing for the Great Eastern.
bios.P1ecbdeb: Colebrook wrote to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company in late 1857 to campaign for the use of the Great Eastern in the South America trades.
bios.P3e8627b: Coleman appears to be one of Russell's chief assistants or counsels. His presence was often requested at meetings between Brunel/Russell or the Eastern Steam Navigation Company and Russell, beginning with the first major financial difficulties faced by Russell in early 1856
bios.P82aa8b2: Brunel corresponded with Conder and Wollaston Blake in mid-1855 about gas illumination, trialled in Paris, for the Great Eastern.
bios.P2dad29d: Coode was a presentative of the town of Portland, Maine, who attempted to correspond with Brunel about the maiden voyage of the Great Eastern.  Coode was attempting to assure Brunel of the suitability of local supplies.
bios.Pdccc3ae: Cooke corresponded with Brunel in early 1856 regarding Piazzi Smyth's instruments
bios.Pedd5216: Joseph Cookson was trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company and legal owner, with four other trustees, of the Great Western steam ship.  He was a member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce and closely acquainted with the Bristol businessmen trying to redevelop the city's trade from the 1820s onward.
bios.P14b0001: Cory Jr was one of many suppliers who contacted Brunel and the Great Ship Company in 1859 to enquire about coaling services for the Great Eastern.  He was a supplier to Joshua Field.
bios.P7b4600e: Crace was employed to fit out cabins on the Great Eastern, during the middle period of construction.
bios.P8fb4403: Captain Crozier (RN) was a shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company from at least 1840.
bios.Pf1eb74d: Thomas Cruttwell was an early shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company - likely Thomas Macauley Cruttwell of Bath, local landowner. Also an associate of Thomas Guppy.
bios.P335ae05: Cumming sent Brunel advice on several screw propellers in contemporary vessels during early 1855, at the earliest build stage of the Great Eastern.
bios.P27e37b6: Cummins offered Brunel an instrument for detecting ice in the North Atlantic, for use on the Great Eastern, which was declined.
bios.P8e92d76: The Cunard Line, launched in 1840 as a British government mail carrier on the North Atlantic, was the first line to succesfully run a continuous service of multiple steamships between Britain and North America.  The firm was an early rival of the GWSSco., who had also bid for the mail contract. During the construction of the Great Eastern, the Line, its staff and suppliers provided information to Brunel and the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  Much of this correspondence concerned enquiries from Brunel about the Cunard ship Persia, which when completed in 1856 was the largest and fastest iron paddle steamer in the world.  In 1855, The Liverpool Corporation, which had previously been contacted by the ESN and on behalf of local railways to ask whether the city locks would be wide enough for the Great Eastern, asked Cunard's advice as 'the most experienced in steam navigation of the port of Liverpool' - the Cunard Line advised the Liverpool Corporation that it was unnecessary to widen the lock gates for the Great Eastern.  Throughout the project, the Cunard Line thus proved supportive of the Great Eastern project whenever enquiries were made.
bios.Ba07e13c: Cundall & Howlett was a photography firm, employed in 1854 to take photographs of progress on the Great Eastern so that Brunel could monitor building work.
bios.P1bb0f53: Cundall was partner in the firm Cundall & Howlett, who were engaged to photograph the progress of the Great Eastern's construction.  For the Great Eastern, Cundall was responsible for the businesses transactions, Howlett for the photography itself.
bios.Pf0ad0a4: James Cunningham was a Bristol merchant and shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.  Cunningham had links to numerous Caribbean plantations and received compensation from the British state after the abolition of slavery: https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/46762
bios.P2927169: D Brown & J Weir offered to supply signal lamps for the Great Eastern.
bios.Pb195913: Arthur J Davey supplied the coal for the Great Eastern's maiden voyage.
bios.P780ad1d: Davis was asked, via William Jacomb, to prepare hawse pipes for the Great Eastern in 1856.
bios.P4db835e: Delaney gave the Eastern Steam Navigation Company information about the work of Westwood & Baillie on the Cunard steamship Persia, largest and fastest in the world in 1856.
bios.P8b76c91: Dent worked at the ordnance lab of the Royal Arsenal, Woolwich, and informed Jacomb and Brunel about fire-retardent for the Great Eastern.
bios.P23de652: In February 1857, Derby won the contract to paint the Great Eastern.
bios.Pe5c299d: Dickson was John Scott Russell's chief foreman at the Millwall works that constructed the Great Eastern.  He was responsible for all of the major mechanical engineering of the Great Eastern's screw engines, including condensers and boilers, as well as the paddle wheels and stern casings.
bios.Pb3cc337: In mid-1857, Dinsmere forwarded Brunel and the Eastern Steam Navigation Company press cuttings from North America which detailed the Great Eastern.  These included the Portland Advertiser, and many others.
bios.Paa42903: Bryan Donkin was an inventor, mechanical engineer, and pioneer of early factory production processes, including food canning (1809).  He met Marc Brunel during his work at Chatham Docks, was a mutual associate of Maudslay, Sons & Field and served as Director of the Thames Tunnel project.  He was asked by Isambard Brunel to survey and review early trunk engine designs for the Great Britain steamship in 1839, which Donkin obliged.
bios.Pff79aaf: Mr Dowell was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.Ped46bc3: Dunn was an employee of Fox & Henderson, who corresponded with Brunel regarding chain cables for the Great Eastern.
bios.P0c62d1e: John Edye was Senior Constructor in the Royal Navy and deputy to William Symonds. He was an advocate for Great Western Steamship company within the Admiralty during the construction of the Great Britain.
bios.Pf74b01b: Engeldrew was a Royal Navy contact to whom Brunel appealed late in the construction of the Great Eastern for recommendations on fitting out.  Brunel also appleaed to long-established ship builder John Laird at the same time.  Engeldrew subseqeuntly recommended a number of foremen and expert carpenters, but there is no record of Lairds reply.
bios.Pdcbc3d1: Essie tendered for the wainscoating of the Great Eastern's cabins in mid-1857.
bios.Pe509620: Evans worked for the Hydrographic Office of the Admiralty, and sent Brunel 3 pamphlets concerning compass deviation in 1855.  He recommended the adoption of the practical rules that were used by the Royal Navy. He also offered whatever assistance he 'could provide in the matter of compasses'.  Evans also recommeded 'Mr Moriarty' to Brunel as a scientific navigator onboard the Great Eastern, which was not, unfortunately, followed up.
bios.Pc4c814e: William Fairbairn was a mechanical and civil engineer and pioneer of iron shipbuilding from 1830.  He supplied vessels to both P&O and the Royal Navy during the mid-1830s.  Fairbairn was consulted by Brunel on construction techniques and equipment early in the process of building the Great Britain, and throughout the design and construction of the Great Eastern.
bios.P923b4b2: F H Falkner was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.Pddb6db2: In mid-1856, Fayrer offered the Great Eastern project use of 'patent safety steering apparatus'.  This was apparently favoured by Scott Russell and already in use on the Great Britain.
bios.Paa2efbb: Ferguson was consulted by Scott-Russell during the early build stages of the Great Eastern [1855] regarding rigging drawings.
bios.P4d667c2: Joshua Field was a pioneering machine and marine Engineer.  He Joined Joseph Maudslay as partner in Maudlsay, Sons & Field from 1822, and assumed control of the company in 1831 upon Maudslays death.  He specialised in marine engines, steam engines and other machinery and was a founding member of Institute of Civil Engineers.  Field designed and built the engines and boilers of the Great Western steamship and built the engines for Great Britain Steamship after a protracted process and effectively as builder of last resort.  He was closely embedded with naval architecture and the marine engineering community on the River Thames, and was in close professional correspondence with other figures involved with the Great Western, such as Oliver Laing and Samuel Hall.  He was brought into the Great Western project on Brunel's strong recommendation, and his ability to deliver the engineering system for the ship was the critical factor in the GWSSCo. launching the first purpose-built Atlantic steamer.  Field served a lesser role on the Great Britain, whose engines were less effective than those on the Great Western.  Field was also consulted by Brunel during the planning stages of the Great Eastern, with Field preferring steam jacketing to high pressure boilers to gain fuel efficiency for the ship, a conclusion which Brunel supported.  This discussion shaped marine steam engineering throughout the 1850s, with high pressure steam under a compound engine arrangement first appearing in 1854, and ultimately proving of far greater efficiency.
bios.Pe7e8e66: Finch was a proponent of iron masts and wrote to Brunel in early 1856 to support the idea of them for the Great Eastern. He had done mast work for Humphrey's Tennant & Dyke, and also provided Brunel with details about the vessel Aerolite, an iron-masted ship which had recently recorded good times on a round voyage from England-Australia-China.  Although Finch had also worked with Brunel on Chepstow bridge, Brunel informed Finch that he would be making iron masts to his own design.
bios.Bb870f61: Forbes, Forbes & Co wrote to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company in mid-1856 to inform them that the Great Eastern represented a patent infringement, seeking payment for an American gentleman named 'Mr Tuft'.
bios.P372eb84: Ford was recommended by Engledrew, RN, to Brunel to lead the fitting out of the Great Eastern.
bios.P9580fc2: Fowler was one of the principal directors of the Great Ship Company, the firm founded to complete the Great Eastern.
bios.P340ae4a: Fowler apparently worked on the construction of the Great Eastern as a subcontractor.  In February 1856 he requested an advance in funds from Brunel, which Brunel explained was difficult to meet, showing the early financial difficulties of the project.
bios.B04182ca: Fox Henderson were Birmingham and London based iron founders that tendered for the manufacture of the Great Eastern's anchors in late 1855.  The firm had previosuly tendered for various ironworks for Paddington Station on behalf of the Great Western Railway.
bios.P1fbe0c5: Dr Charles Fox was a Bath-based shareholder of the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P02d2b82: Fox wrote to Brunel from Falmouth in 1855 recommending his portable instrument for testing magnetic interference.
bios.B1aa9b58: Fred Krupps Cast Steel Iron Works was the employer of Alfred Longsdon. Longsdon unsuccesfully petitioned Brunel to have the Great Eastern's main crankshaft forged in steel when it became clear that iron forgings were hugely problematic.  Brunel rebuked the concept of steel, then exlored its potential benefits in a long letter to Longsdon, before concluding that the material was too novel a risk for the Great Eastern project.
bios.P2db2143: Joseph Freeman was an employee of the Lowmoor Iron Co, who corresponded with Brunel regarding types of finished iron for the Great Eastern.  However, as Lowmoor were unable to produce certain parts, they do not appear to have become a supplier.
bios.Pce689ef: French was hired in early 1859 as an estimator for the costs of internal fittings on the Great Eastern.  This included cabins and a potential poop deck.
bios.P28d669a: Charles Freshfield was the solicitor who represented both the Eastern Steam Navigation Company and John Scott Russell.
bios.P7eb376e: Charles Bowles Fripp was auditor for the Great Western Steam Ship Company.  He was a senior director of the Great Western Railway, and member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce.
bios.P22abbac: William Froude was a long term engineering assistant of Brunel, originally on the Great Western Railway.  He committed significant time to calculating the moment of inertia during a ships roll between waves to try and help with the stability of the Great Eastern, although his calcuations only began in late 1856, years after the hull design and architecture of the vessel had been decided.
bios.P7814c2e: Geach was a Birmingham-based banker, business partner of iron-founder Thomas Walker, and was an original director and principal shareholder in the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  He is credited with being the financial driving force behind the Great Eastern.  He was involved as either a director or supplier of the Shrewsbury & Birmingham Railway, the South Devon Railway, and the South Wales Railway, on which he worked with Edward Finch and Brunel to produce Chepstow Bridge.  Geach served as mayor of Birmingham in the 1840s and MP for Westminster at the time of his death.  His estate was represented by Birmingham solicitors Beale & Co., represented in the Great Eastern project by Samuel Beale, and another of his Midland business partners was Charles Yates [potential relation to John Yates, ESN Director]. Geach died early in the ESN project, in December 1854, which placed the company and ship in financial difficulty.
bios.P62b511c: George Gibbs was a shareholder in the Great Western, later owner of the Great Britain, and member of a Bristol merchant family linked to Caribbean and Antipodean trade.  He was business partner of Robert Bright from 1823 onward, engaging in dry goods trading in the Caribbean.  He was a member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce, director and major investor in Great Western Railway, and shareholer in the Great Western Steamship Company, from which Gibbs retired in 1839. The firm of Gibbs, Bright Company acquired the Great Britain from the Great Western Steam Ship Co. in 1850 and operated it to Australia for 26 years, although George Gibbs was in retirment at the time of the acquisition, and died in 1863.  The parent company of Gibbs, Bright Company, Anthony Gibbs & Co., acquired and operated the vessel from 1882 gto 1886.  Gibbs received payments in compensation from the British state after the abolition of slavery, through joint and counterclaims to various estates:  https://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/2725
bios.Pd3648d7: George H Gibbs was son of Anthony Gibbs of Tyntesfield, and cousin of George Gibbs, the later nominal owner of the Great Britain.   It was however George H, and not the latter owner of the Great Britain with whom Brunel had a close working relationship. George H was a major investor in the Great Western Railway, in which he was closely involved, as well an investor in the Great Western Steam Ship company.  He corresponded closely with Brunel and was given a private tour of Maudslay & Fields engines for the Great Western when on business with Brunel in London.
bios.P836845c: Gibson was a papier mache supplier who sought custom on the Great Eastern's fitting out.  Gibson also offered flame-retardent wood paint.
bios.P3a2871c: Gladstone offered improvements to ships masts to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company in 1856.
bios.Pbf00d77: Henry Godwin was an early investor in the Great Western Steamship Company and was appointed a director of the firm in 1838.
bios.Pc808cdf: Daniel Gooch was the locomotive designer and manufacturer for the Great Western Railway.  A close ally of Brunel, in October 1856 Brunel attempted to have Gooch appointed as a Director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  Gooch was later a director of the Great Ship Company, formed to complete the Great Eastern, and in 1865 took ownsership of the vessel, converting it to a cable-layer in the only profitable application the vessel ever found.  The potential for the Great Eastern as a cable layer was recognised even during the construction phase, as a principal manufactory of marine telegraph cable was operating opposite the Great Eastern's construction site.
bios.P35e89c8: In 1855, Brunel enquired if Gordon knew of any oil-gas apparatus (for the Great Eastern) that was already well-tested.
bios.P6ed0a5f: Grant offered cooking and catering systems for the Great Eastern which he had perfected at military camps in Aldershot.
bios.Pe75c0d1: John Grantham was a pioneering iron shipbuilder, based in Liverpool.  He built several small coastwise and river iron steamers and published a treatise on iron ship building in 1842.  He corresponded with Brunel early in the construction of the Great Britain, and extensively with Guppy during its construction.  He was a mutual associate of the Rennies and designed the first Atlantic iron screw steamer to be launched after the Great Britain, the Sarah Sands, in 1847.  Brunel was wary of Grantham's influence within the ICE and among iron ship builders, and remonstrated heavily with GWSSco. directors not to take up Grantham's offer of correcting faults in the Great Britain that emerged when it began operating.
bios.Pc24b60c: Green was a representative of Sims & Muntz, asked to inspect the Great Eastern before casting a rudder for the ship.
bios.P63fad8c: Gregory sent Brunel advice early in 1855 regarding water tanks for the Great Eastern.
bios.Pf9eecfb: Robert Griffiths was a marine engineer who, via Christopher Claxton, was canvassed for information for the Great Eastern.  He provided information about the propeller of the Great Britain, anthracite coal, and the stern and screw of the ship Agamemnon [1852].  Griffiths also invited Brunel to observe his work in Liverpool on screw propellers for the Royal Navy and United States Navy - work which was endorsed for Griffiths by Bernard Matthews, commander of the Great Western, Great Britain, and City of Glasgow.  Matthews, a former cpatain for the GWSSCo., was regarded as one of the nations leading experts on marine propulsion.
bios.Pd45ba37: Grissell supplied planks for the fitting of cabins in the Great Eastern.
bios.P4d8bebd: Thomas Guppy was a Bristol sugar merchant, manufacturer, and engineer.  A Founding member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce, Guppy was one of four individuals credited with the founding of the Great Western Railway.  In contemporary sources, notably the company's second AGM, he is also credited as the original projector of the Great Western Steamship Company.  As the only member of both the BCC and GWSSco. who had experience with North Atlantic trade (as owner of a sugar refinery in New York, which he ran with his brother Samuel), and as the earliest known proponent of rail and steam connections for Bristol, Guppy's founding role in the Great Western endeavours, both local and international, was decisive.  Guppy served as director of Great Western Steamship Company from its first inception, and later as resident engineer during the latter half of the Great Britain's construction, working closely with Brunel and William Patterson.
bios.P58ef282: Samuel Hall was a boiler maker for marine steam engines.  His condensing principles appear to have been adopted by Joshua Field for the boilers of the Great Western.   He was heavily admonished by Brunel for claiming that Field gained contracts through favouritism.
bios.B938c418: Hansons Olefiant Gas Co, offered gas lighting for the Great Eastern, which was not taken up.
bios.P4b0d49b: Mr Harding was a member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce and shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P692a49f: John Hare was a Member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce and shareholder in Great Western Steam Ship Company. He was a whig candidate and political oponent of Christopher Claxton over the issue of abolition.
bios.P313f785: John Harford was partner of Philip John Miles in the bank Miles, Harford & Co., which was the bank of both the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship Company.  He was trustee of the Great Western Steamship Company and legal owner, with four other trustees, of the Great Western steam ship.
bios.Ped24684: Harrison was appointed captain of the Great Eastern in November 1855.  Brunel believed it critically important that any captain of the ship understood it as a working system, and expressed this to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company board early in the build.  Harrison would therefore have had a chance to get to know the ship as it was constructed.  He was however killed before the first voyage, when his boat carrying him to shore from the ship at Southampton capsized.
bios.Pbdde4ff: Silver, Harrison, Leaf Howard & Co were Thomas Silver, J W Harrison, H L Leaf and Howard, Philadelphia attorneys.  They outlined an American patent to the Eastern Steam Navigation Company for the 'governor' Brunel wished to to use for the Great Eastern, claiming Brunel was in breach of patent.  On December 1, 1856, the firm backed down from the claim, as an original patent on the governor was traced to Marc Brunel.  The company then asked Brunel for assistance on the English patent of their own version.
bios.P773554a: In mid-1857, Hart offered Brunel a paddle wheel design for the Great Eastern.  Hart claimed to have mislaid it years before, but wanted to try it out on the ship.  Brunel declined.
bios.B1f60389: Hartley & Co were engaged to estimate felting for the boilers of the Great Eastern.
bios.Bf4ea2ac: Harvey & Co were asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855.
bios.B2330916: Hawkes & Crayshaw were asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855, and its rudder in November 1856.
bios.Pdef47b7: Hawkshaw was a long time colleague of Brunel.  With the founding of the Great Ship Company to clomplete the Great Eastern, Hawkshaw was appointed along with John Fowler and William McLean as arbiters of the contract between John Scott Russell and the GSC to complete the ship.
bios.P0a66d07: George Hay worked for Milne & Sons, who wereinitially to build observational instruments for the Great Eastern.  These were to be to the designs of C. Piazzi Smyth, but but Hay was unable to satisfactorily complete them.
bios.Pbed6023: Hedger wrote to Brunel late in 1856 with information about 'Day's Cement', its use in decking, and its use on the Great Britain.
bios.B441e4a7: Wood & Co were engaged in early 1857 to make chain cable for the Great Eastern and for its launch.  Unable to manufacture the thickest width of chain link (6 inches) - a contract that went to Brown Lenox - Wood instead manufactured 2-inch chain.  The company was also engaged to cast the Great Eastern's anchors to John Trotman's design, ultimately providing faulty anchors.
bios.P2df3729: Hepplewhite sent Brunel designs for a spare rudder for the Great Eastern in late 1855.
bios.Pb93656f: Hepworth was the the foreman at John Scott Russell's yard in Millwall.  He was directly responsible for the physical construction of the Great Eastern's fabric, including the hull, stern, ports, paddle boxes, rudder, and painting of the vessel.
bios.Pab88ec5: Heseltine was referred to Brunel by E L Berthon as a possible assistant with sounding leads for the Greeat Eastern.
bios.P83882ce: Hevens was an associate of R J Fayrer, who asked Brunel if Hevens could visit the Great Eastern site to dicuss steering apparatus.
bios.Bbe9cba2: Hingley & Co were asked to tender for chain cable supplies for the Great Eastern in 1857, but failed to gain a contract.
bios.B9866515: Hoare & Barnetts were London solicitors of both the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.Pd000546: Hohn was a marine engineer based in Greenock, Scotland, the epicentre of ocean steam ship building by the mid-1850s.  He offered Brunel propeller designs for the Great Eastern which had been purchased by the French Navy, however, Brunel broke off correspondence with Hohn after Hohn raised inefficiencies with the propeller in HMS Rattler, the experimental warship for which Brunel provided propeller designs in the 1840s.
bios.Pc98c46a: Liverpool-based Holderness provided Brunel with drawings of the iron 'Unicorn' mast, popular with steam ships, in early 1857.
bios.Pfb0d9b8: In late 1856, Holmes offered Brunel 'at very reasonable cost' the use of an electric lighting system for the Great Eastern.  This was not used.
bios.B1e24315: Hood & Cooper were asked in November 1856 to tender for casting of the SS Great Eastern's rudder.
bios.P8be8c6b: Henry Hope was a director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  He was the first to suggest the use of the South Wales Railway link to Milford Haven to establish a dock there for the Great Eastern, which did not come to fruition.  The ship did dock there for repairs in 1862, however, when another railway contractor, Rowland Brotherhood, of Chippenham provided replacement paddle wheels to the storm damaged ship.
bios.Pb30aa0e: Horsefell was head of the Horsefell Mersey Steel & Iron Co.
bios.B5a913f3: Horsefell were asked in November 1856 to tender for casting of the SS Great Eastern's rudder.
bios.Pc8270b7: Horstman was a friend of Yates who contacted Brunel in early 1857 with a boiler design for the Great Eastern.  This was likely as a result of the difficulties the Eastern Steam Navigation Company were having with Watt & Co.'s boilers, but Hortsman's went unused.
bios.Pfb4d5cd: How offered a system of telegraph communications for the Great Eastern's engine room, which were not taken up.
bios.B6672c4f: Howard & Ravenshill were asked in November 1856 to tender for casting of the SS Great Eastern's rudder.
bios.P1664700: Howard corresponded with Brunel in 1857 about the pre-heating of steam to increase efficiency in marine engines.  Howard had recently published work in Mechanics Magazine, and Brunel commented to him that 'until new methods are invented that can be applied to the big ship' (Great Eastern), he would continue to use the method of steam jacketing to pre-heat steam for its engines.  In 1854, John Elder, a Glaswegian marine engineer, had created and deployed the safer and more efficient high-pressure compound engine, which was emerging as the most efficient industry model by the time of the Great Eastern's first voyage across the Atlantic.  Steam jacketing was ultimately found to be the root of the funnel explosion which killed three men during the Great Eastern's trials.
bios.Pd48ad12: Huddart contacted the Eastern Steam Navigation Company late in 1856 to ask permission to tender for cordage.
bios.B23cd8c1: Deptford-based marine engineers, headed by Edward Humphrys, which unsuccesfully tendered for the propeller-engine contract of the Great Eastern.  Brunel sought advice from Edward Humphrys at various points in the planning and construction of the Great Eastern, but Humphrys Tennant & Dyke never gained any formal contracts to contribute to the ship.  Edward Humphrys would introduce the fuel efficient compound engine to P&O steamers in 1861, one year after the Great Eastern was launched.
bios.P61a42bd: Humphrys was a Thames-based marine engineer, and lead in the firm of Humphry's, Tennant and Dyke.  Humphry's largely built for the Royal Navy, and introduced the first compund engine to Royal Navy vessels in 1861.
bios.P00249ed: Francis Humphrys was hired as superintending engineer on the Great Britain Steamship, and provided initial engine designs.  In constant friction with Brunel over engine design who disliked Humphry's trunk engine, Humphry's died in 1841, suceeded by Thomas Guppy as superintending engineer.
bios.P903a9aa: Hutchison wrote to Brunel in 1855, effectively suggesting a 'bumper' design for steam vessels.
bios.Pde42eec: George Hutt was John Yates' contact at Beale & Co, who corresponded with Brunel about the supply of a specialized iron plate for the Great Eastern.  The plates were eventually supplied but there was confusion as to the price - Yates being apparently offered a better price than Brunel himself.
bios.P8f70d74: George Inman, of Poplar, submitted designs for the Great Eastern's cabins in mid-1856.
bios.P7ff6cde: Richard Irvin was agent for the Great Western Steamship Company in New York.  Responsible for receiving incoming freights and brokering return freights and tickets, fuel supplies and crewing for the Great Western and Great Britain.  In early 1856, Irvin was astounded to learn that the Eastern Steam Navigation Company were considering using Portland, Maine, as the American port of disembarkation for the Great Eastern, writing directly to Christopher Claxton to ask why New York was not being used, on account of having financial and navigational advantages, exisitng available docking, and an ease of transfer for goods and people into the city.  The decision against New York was never explained - the decision for Portland seems to have rested on the fact that two leading ESN directors had railway interests there.
bios.P9379f38: Isaac was contacted by Brunel to supply boards for lining the cabins of the Great Eastern.  He apologised to Brunel that he 'couldn't read Brunel's letter', but for Brunel to enquire with Samuel Brothers or the Samuda Brothers (mutual associates of he and Brunel) about the quality of his supplies.
bios.B53c5204: Ruthen appear to be Edinburgh-based engineers who forwarded Brunel information on improvements to propelling in a Prussian vessel during 1855. This seems to have been a form of water jet or hose.  The prototype seems to have had some crossover with James Braidwoods design, as Brunel and Ruthen discussed it, but Brunel did not see how he could help further the design until he had experiment results.
bios.B312a860: J & R Mitchsion were asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855.
bios.B18dce98: J & White submitted prices for the Great Eastern's lifeboats in 1855.
bios.B296d784: J Abbots & Co were asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855.
bios.B06dccb4: James Russell offered steel tubing for internal fixings on the Great Eastern in early 1857.
bios.Ba37e6a3: J Taylor & Sons offered to estimate for 'metalwork' on the Great Eastern, but were not engaged.
bios.B3871a82: J Tylor & Sons submitted designs for the Great Eastern's interior, apparently being the closet and wardrobe spaces.
bios.B0df22d9: J W Gray & Sons were marine engineering suppliers, who sent details of various lines of business to Eastern Steam Navigation Company in 1856.
bios.P78e9e24: Captain Jackson (RN) assisted with docking and surveying of the Great Western after its first year of service.  He was also routinely consulted regardng fire retardent processes for ships timbers during the construction of the Great Eastern, and ultimately provided the planking for the ships' deck.
bios.P83e09a3: Jacomb was one of Brunel's senior engineering assistants, and principal representative on the Milwall site where the Great Eastern was constructed.  He was repeatedly called to verify volumes of work completed and goods ordered, especially when Brunel accused Scott Russell of embezzling iron supplies or otherwise of slow progress.
bios.B8469074: James & Nevill were Plymouth-based shipwrights, contacted by William Patterson regarding hull-painting and fouling for the Great Eastern.
bios.B1642471: Watt & Co., of Birmingham, tendered for construction of the Great Eastern's propeller engines in May, 1853, and were subsequently awarded the contract.  The engines and there construction proved unsatisfactory at first completion, and a constant source of friction between Brunel and Watt & Co.'s principal engineer, Henry Wollaston Blake.
bios.B30bf441: John & Robert White offered to supply lifeboats to the Great Eastern, apparently on recommendation of Cpt Harrison.
bios.Bf0ebda4: Greenock engineering firm that employed C A Hohn.
bios.B0853172: John Gray & Son were asked to tender for ship's scuttles for the Great Eastern in Spring 1857.
bios.P74758cf: A P Johnson was a shareholder in the Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P1ef2e88: Jones was consulted by Brunel regarding coal supplies for the Great Eastern in July 1859.

bios.P5936e10: During Lancefield Forge's troubles with fabricating the main crankshaft of the Great Eastern, Longsdon wrote to Brunel to offer a steel forging.  Longsdon argued this would be both lighter and stronger and provided accompanying information of similar weights of steel forged by his firm for other engineers and for the French government.  His firm was Krupp's Cast Steel Works, possible progenitor of the major European steelmaker.  Brunel replied that he could not possibly risk a new material on such a key part of the ship, that he was 'doubtful very much would come of it [steel]', but nonetheless asked for extensive technical data.  The offer, and refusal, of a new material for the crankshaft which would have solved a significant technical problem with the Great Eastern is a clear example of the ship's concept being too large for existing materials and techniques, but too oversized and expensive to be innovative.
bios.P3651106: Josiah Lorkin - who was not a prior associate - wrote to Brunel on 3 December, 1856 with comparative calorific and cost data on Welsh and Pennsylvanian Anthracite. He provided data for the economy, on the Atlantic run, of collecting return coals from Philadelphia, and the inefficiency of carrying out-and-return loads of Welsh coal.  The letter was not reciprocated, but is one of the most significant pieces of correspondence in the Great Eastern project.  It demonstrates firstly that a U.S. route for the Great Eastern was both widely accepted and publicly known by the mid-point of the ships' construction, negating the need for a vessel engineered to carry coals to India or Australia, and secondly, that both Brunel and the Eastern Steam Navigation Company were ignorant of marine fueling on the Atlantic route, which made ships with oversized fuel capacity unneccesary and inefficient.  It is a letter that suggests that, even by the mid-point of its construction, the Great Eastern as a project and concept had become obsolete.

bios.P4e870c0: William Patterson was a Bristol ship-builder who drew lines of and constructed hulls for both the Great Western and Great Britain steam ships.  Patterson was from Greenock, Scotland, began his ship-building career in London in the 1820s, and arrived in Bristol in 1830.  He developed a number of pioneering vessels that drew local acclaim, including the schooner 'Velox' in 1833, and large paddle steamers for the British and Irish coasting trade.  The first of these, the 'County of Pembroke' was built for Thomas Guppy's brother Samuel in 1834, but immediately sold as Samuel was running the Guppy Sugar Company in New York; the captain of the Pembroke, Bernard Matthews, would go on to be lieutenant and later captain of the Great Western, as well as the Great Britain.  Matthews was also one of the part owners of the Pembroke, as was John Moxham, future auditor of the GWSSCo., and George Lunnell, one of the business pioneers of the Bristol steam packet trade.  In 1835, Patterson produced the slightly larger 'Mountaneer', a paddle steamer for the Swansea & Liverpool Co., built for the tough passage between these two cities.  This record of building large paddle steamers, as well as connections to the Guppy family and local investors led to Patterson's selection as builder of the Great Western.  He integrated all pioneering suggestions in the design and build of the hull as proposed by other contributors to the project, including those of Oliver Lang at the Royal Navy.  Patterson later drew the lines for, and superintended the construction of the Great Britain's hull at the newly cut GWSSCo. drydock, and was also consulted by Brunel on minor points during the construction of the Great Eastern, where he was also employed to assess the ship during sea trials.

In mid-1856, John Yates encouraged Brunel to work with 'Mr Penn', and the two developed a cordial exchange, in which Penn offered advice on developing shafts for the Great Eastern's screw engine, recommended the Great Britain's ship engineer, Alexander McLennan, for similar duties on the Great Eastern, and offered advice on launching the ship.  Penn also made his yard, on the opposite side of the Thames, available as an anchoring point to help launch the Great Eastern.

bios.P7f1e6b3: Alexander Ross was a contact in Portland, Maine, who worked on behalf of that port to secure it as the Great Eastern's Atlantic port of landing.  In 1855, Ross gave the Great Eastern's newly appointed captain (Harrison) a tour of the port, and requested that Brunel send the distance, in width, that new jetties at Portland would need to be to accomodate the ship.  It is evident from this detailed early planning that the Atlantic had been selected as the arena of trade for the Great Eastern early in the construction phase, with India and Australia abandoned almost instantly.  The decision to send the ship onto the Atlantic in 1860 was not, therefore, a last minute decision for the maiden voyage.

bios.Bae64d0a: St Helens Ironworks offered to forge the crankshaft the Great Eastern project was struggling with in late 1857.
bios.Pe28fa9a: John Stafford was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P97b1ab6: Statham responded to Brunel about the production of rubber tubing for sounding leads in 1855.
bios.P0c05bf5: Mr Stedder was a Bath-based investor in Great Western Railway and Great Western Steamship.
bios.P33b06c9: John Edward Stephens was a director of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.
bios.Pa574f11: Stobbs offered hydraulic systems for the Great Easterns engine pumps in late 1857, after those components had already been completed.
bios.Pb94be66: Mr J Stone was asked to tender for ship's scuttles for the Great Eastern in Spring 1857.
bios.B9d5b3d9: Swain, Stevens & Co were  London-based solicitors for the Great Western Railway and Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P684f9fe: William Symonds was Surveyor of the Royal Navy from 1830-1847.  He was immediate superior of Oliver Lang and was thanked by the Great Western Steamship Company for liberal assistance in providing naval drawings for the Great Western steam ship.  He also corresponded with Brunel throughout propeller trials on the HMS Rattler, which Brunel was invited to super-intend, and which informed decisions made on the Great Britain.
bios.B2230561: T & W Forester submitted prices for the Great Eastern's lifeboats in 1855.
bios.P8f5f552: Christopher Talbot was Chairman of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company.  He served as Chairman for Brunel's South Wales Railway throughout the 1850s.
bios.Pfc88776: Taunton offered the Great Eastern a design for portable boats in 1857, which was not taken up.
bios.P37b31ae: Taylor offered Brunel/the Eastern Steam Navigation Company an invention for registering the course of a sea-going vessel, for use in the Great Eastern.  This was rejected by Brunel for being too similar to his own ideas.
bios.Pfdc0585: John Taylor was a member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce and shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.P8307252: Reverend Taylor was a shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.B72a8d5b: Thames Ironworks tendered for casting of the Great Eastern's rudder in December 1856, under the name C J Mare & Company.
bios.Bfe880bf: Thames Plate Glass Co were asked to tender for the cabin lights of the Great Eastern in the Spring of 1857.
bios.P0016717: Thompson submitted prices for the Great Eastern's lifeboats in 1855.
bios.Pb5b2b33: Robert Thomson was an employee of the Cunard Line, who wrote to Brunel and the Great Ship Company to recommend coal suppliers for the Great Eastern in 1859.
bios.Pcb86e98: John Trotman was asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855.  Although unsuccessful, in early 1857 his patented anchor deisgn was accepted as the model for the Great Eastern, although Henry Wood Co., chosen to manufacture anchors, struggled with their fabrication.
bios.Bb37a749: Troughton and Bevan sent Brunel advice in 1855 for lowering and disengaging ships' boats.
bios.P1562afc: Edwin Turner was an employee of the Bowling Iron Co, who corresponded with Brunel regarding types of finished iron for the Great Eastern.  However, as Bowling were unable to produce certain parts, they do not appear to have become a supplier.
bios.P72fa3d1: Turner sent Brunel advice on using English Larch in the Great Eastern in early 1855.
bios.P495cb83: Viney was an employee of Watt & Co who corresponded with Brunel in 1855 regarding pistons.
bios.Pf5e88ba: John Vining was trustee of the Great Western Steam Ship Company and legal owner, with four other trustees of the Great Western steam ship. He was a member of Bristol Chamber of Commerce, member of the Merchant Venturers and director of the Great Western Railway.
bios.B98bfc47: W Morgan & Son offered hemp cordage supplies to the Great Eastern in 1857.
bios.B845f4a2: Wainright Bros offered iron yards to the Great Eastern, however it is not clear whether they gained a contract.
bios.P315383f: Wakefield was one of Brunel's assistants assigned tasks at the construction site of the Great Eastern, including helping John Scott Russell.  He also corresonded with R P Brereton, Brunel's chief assistant, in early 1856 regarding the cost of riveting on some of Brunel's other projects - notably the Plymouth Pontoon and the Great Britain.  The correspondence was timed with emerging concerns about the financial management at the yard where the Great Eastern was under construction.
bios.P6a4bd95: Walker was recommeded to Brunel for information on anchors in the Great Eastern.
bios.Pfe4e160: Walker, of the Patent Axle Tree works, was commissioned by Brunel in December 1856 to cast a number of hollow axles for the Great Eastern.
bios.Pd902cc0: Early in the Great Eastern's planning, Walker was consulted by Brunel on navigational and mechanical issues, particularly compasses. Walker attributed the grounding of the Great Britain at Dundrum Bay to its compasses.
bios.Pec20302: Mr Warr was a Shareholder in the Great Western Steam Ship Company and Great Western Railway.
bios.Be42bc9d: Watkins and Hill were canvassed for information for an on-board instrument in the Great Eastern.
bios.Pa0d16f6: Thomas Boneville Were was an investor in and director of Great Western Steamship Company.
bios.P9bd0166: White was contacted as a supplier for life boats on the Great Eastern.
bios.P644aef2: In late 1857, White offered to build a floating harbour for the Great Eastern in Melbourne.  His offer did not receive a reply. It is one of only two mentions to docking in Australia in the correspondence of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company from the inception of the Great Eastern in 1852 to its completion in 1859, suggesting that the publicity and rationale around Australian steaming was never seriously reflected in the planning and construction of the ship.  Rather, planning for docking in Portland, Maine, began early, and was maintained throughout the ships construction.
bios.P8ca3b3c: Whitehead appears to have been responsible for the casting of the Great Eastern's screw propeller.
bios.Bafce4b1: Wilkins & Weatherly requested permission to tender for wire rope or standard rigging rope for the Great Eastern. They were based at the Submarine Telegraph & Wire Rope Works, Wapping, and made the offer in 1855. In Spring of 1857 they were asked to tender.
bios.P3173f4b: Wilkins sent Brunel advice on launching the Great Eastern early in 1855, alongside information on gas fittings.
bios.B879bda8: William Day & Co, via Claxton, offered to provide 'coating' for the Great Eastern.  They were based in the vicinity of Millwall/Rotherhithe.
bios.B35d7c1f: William Kuper & Co (latterly Glass Elliott & Co) were asked to tender for iron rigging for the Great Eastern in Spring 1857.
bios.Pe7b43bf: Williams was supplier of coal to R W Jones.
bios.P23b71c7: Williams was a manufacturer of distilling apparatus for ship water, who approached Brunel about supplying the Great Eastern in early 1857.
bios.P9224822: Williams was an employee of the patent shaft company, who contacted Brunel about intermediate shafts for the Great Eastern paddle engines. They found their machinery too limited for the Brunel's needs.
bios.P2d53dc8: John Winwood was a Bristol marine engineer.  He engined the first Bristol-fitted packet steamers for coastwise trade in the 1820s, and tendered to build engines for Great Western, but was unsuccessful. Briefly auditor of Great Western Steamship Compnay in 1838-9, he retired 1840.
bios.Pb053f01: During the Lancefield Forge's troubles with forming the main crankshaft for the Great Eastern, Wise enquired with Brunel about making the shaft. Brunel maintained the order with Lancefield.
bios.P3773682: Albert Wood was partner in Wood & Co, suppliers of chain cable to the Great Eastern.
bios.B4942cf4: Woods Bros, of Liverpool, were asked to tender for the Great Easterns chain cables in December 1855.
bios.Pa938091: In 1855 Brunel enquired about lifeboats with Wright.
bios.P3b6fcf5: In late 1857, Wyld offered a ventilation system for the Great Eastern, which was not taken up.
bios.Pf070b82: Yates was the secretary of the Eastern Steam Navigation Company, and its managing representative for the Great Eastern project.  He was an occassional mediator between Russell and Brunel.
bios.P79cd793: Robert Young was a marine engineer and mutual correspondent of Brunel and John Laird.
bios.P8001b5c: Assistand engineer to Edward Humphrys on the Great Britain.  Apparently recruitred by Humphry's away from Maudslay, Sons & Field, to Brunel's consternation, Brunel came to hold Harman in high regard during the project.
